Of the physiologically active substances in Cordyceps, Cordycepin (3â€™-deoxyadenosine, 
 Fig. 1) is currently recognized as the index component. Cordycepin was first isolated from 
 C. militaris culture filtrates by 
 Cunningham et al. (1950). The pharmacological effects of Cordycepin, such as antitumor, immunomodulation, anti-inflammatory, antiviral, anti-leukemia, anticancer, antidiabetic, and anti-obesity effects have been revealed, demonstrating the possibility of Cordycepin as a treatment or preventative material against various human diseases (
